==English==

===Etymology===
15th Century, from {{etyl|fro}} from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|absorbeo|absorbeō}} from {{term|ab-||from}}, + {{term|sorbeo|sorbeō|suck in}}.  Compare French {{term|absorber}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əbˈzɔːb/; /əbˈsɔːb/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈzɔːrb/; /æbˈsɔːrb/}}
* {{audio|en-us-absorb.ogg|Audio (US)}}

* {{rhymes|ɔː(r)b}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To [[include]] so that it no longer has [[separate]] existence; to [[swallow up]]; to [[engulf]]; to [[overwhelm]]; to cause to [[disappear]] as if by [[swallowing]] up; to [[use up]]; to [[incorporate]]; to [[assimilate]].
#* Dark oblivion soon '''absorbs''' them all. - [[w:William Cowper|William Cowper]]
#* The large cities '''absorb''' the wealth and fashion. - [[w:Washington Irving|Washington Irving]]
# {{transitive}} To [[suck up]]; to [[drink in]]; to [[imbibe]]; as a [[sponge]] or as the [[lacteals]] of the body. - [[w:Francis Bacon|Francis Bacon]]
# {{transitive}} To [[learn]]
# {{transitive}} To [[engross]] or [[engage]] wholly; to [[occupy]] fully; as, '''absorbed''' in study or in the [[pursuit]] of wealth.
# {{transitive}} To [[consume]] completely.
# {{transitive}} To [[endure]].
# {{transitive}} {{physics}} To take up by [[chemical]] or [[physical]] action.
#: ''Heat, light, and electricity are '''absorbed''' in the substances into which they pass.''
# {{transitive|business}} To assume or pay for as part of a [[commercial]] [[transaction]].

